elp avoid complications. If I load Mojarra as the app on line 123, it seems like I wouldn’t reach line 154. I wonder if using a custom `ResourceBundle.Control` with a classloader might be a solution since `MessageFactory` relies on `ResourceBundle.getBundle`. \\n\\nHmm, if I use a custom classloader that overrides `getResource`, maybe I could avoid native embedded resources. Great idea! I can set the context classloader to supply in-memory properties, allowing `ResourceBundle.getBundle` to fetch from it and bypass metadata issues.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Refining testing approach**\\n\\nI’m looking at the existing tests, which use classpath resources. It seems like I can refine the `MessageFactoryTest` to leverage a custom thread context classloader (TCCL) and minimize reliance on properties. However, I still want to keep some resources. \\n\\nI need to make sure the classloader can effectively delegate class loading, and I remember that `ResourceBundle` may cache by loader. It would be best to use a unique loader for each test and clear the cache afterward to prevent any static issues.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_aJocqeV4m8Dev3Im4n6t6gF3|fc_09ab6edfd708da5c016a01f88419e881939113cc21e523e7a2", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/jakarta.platform/jakarta.jakartaee-api/10.0.0/src/test/java/jakarta_platform/jakarta_jakartaee_api/MessageFactoryTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.util.ArrayList;\nimport java.util.Collections;\nimport java.util.HashMap;\nimport java.util.Iterator;\nimport java.util.List;\nimport java.util.Locale;\nimport java.util.Map;\n", "newText": "import java.io.ByteArrayInputStream;\nimport java.io.IOException;\nimport java.io.InputStream;\nimport java.net.URL;\nimport java.net.URLConnection;\nimport java.net.URLStreamHandler;\nimport java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;\nimport java.util.ArrayList;\nimport java.util.Collections;\nimport java.util.HashMap;\nimport java.util.Iterator;\nimport java.